    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 93,
    "last_activity_date" : 1403702719,
    "creation_date" : 1403702719,
    "answer_id" : 24410004,
    "question_id" : 15054086,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>\"Atomic operation\" means an operation that appears to be instantaneous from the perspective of all other threads. You don't need to worry about a partly complete operation when the guarantee applies.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 221893,
      "reputation" : 7506,
      "user_id" : 480120,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/Y2gc7.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Kurt Zhong",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/480120/kurt-zhong"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 21,
    "last_activity_date" : 1412064218,
    "last_edit_date" : 1412064218,
    "creation_date" : 1411969251,
    "answer_id" : 26093164,
    "question_id" : 15054086,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Just found a post <a href=\"http://preshing.com/20130618/atomic-vs-non-atomic-operations/\">Atomic vs. Non-Atomic Operations</a> to be very helpful to me.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>\"An operation acting on shared memory is atomic if it completes in a single step relative to other threads. </p>\n  \n  <p>When an atomic store is performed on a shared memory, no other thread can observe the modification half-complete. </p>\n  \n  <p>When an atomic load is performed on a shared variable, it reads the entire value as it appeared at a single moment in time.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 10228169,
      "reputation" : 181,
      "user_id" : 7549946,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/d4F4a.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Eugene Shamkin",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7549946/eugene-shamkin"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1586762083,
    "creation_date" : 1586762083,
    "answer_id" : 61183087,
    "question_id" : 15054086,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In Java reading and writing fields of all types except long and double occurs atomically, and if the field is declared with the volatile modifier, even long and double are atomically read and written. That is, we get 100% either what was there, or what happened there, nor can there be any intermediate result in the variables.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 10887284,
      "reputation" : 874,
      "user_id" : 8004365,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/cIyv5.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Malik Mussabeheen Noor",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8004365/malik-mussabeheen-noor"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1661545590,
    "creation_date" : 1661545590,
    "answer_id" : 73506172,
    "question_id" : 15054086,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In simple words, the atomic means the operation will be either completed or not.\nThe other threads or CPUs won't catch it in the middle of the operation.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9378438,
      "reputation" : 1337,
      "user_id" : 8504033,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/48c7c7f25b9c7ba3e9348f52d92eb489?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Abdul Alim Shakir",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8504033/abdul-alim-shakir"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1723107314,
    "creation_date" : 1723107314,
    "answer_id" : 78847433,
    "question_id" : 15054086,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>According to <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/concurrency/atomic.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Oracle</a>,</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>In programming, an atomic action is one that effectively happens all\nat once. An atomic action cannot stop in the middle: it either happens\ncompletely, or it doesn't happen at all. No side effects of an atomic\naction are visible until the action is complete.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The shared resource in multithreading usually causes complex issues when concurrency is applied. The program or database may become inconsistent if a shared resource is impacted. Handling with the shared resource becomes essential where multiple threads access and modify shared resources. In such a case, one of the options may be an atomic variable. And there is no need of explicit synchronization using <code>synchronized</code> or <code>volatile</code> keyword.</p>\n<p>Java package <code>java.util.concurrent.atomic</code> provides the following atomic classes to enable lock free mechanism and thread safety.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/atomic/AtomicBoolean.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">AtomicBoolean</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/atomic/AtomicInteger.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">AtomicInteger</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/atomic/AtomicIntegerArray.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">AtomicIntegerArray</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/atomic/AtomicLong.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">AtomicLong</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/atomic/AtomicLongArray.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">AtomicLongArray</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/atomic/AtomicReference.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">AtomicReference</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/atomic/AtomicReferenceArray.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">AtomicReferenceArray</a></p>\n<p>When two threads work simultaneously on a shared variable and one of those actions involves writing, both threads have to employ atomic operations. The operations of atomic classes in Java depend on CAS(Compare-And-Swap) to perform atomically, ensuring correctness and efficiency of the program in a multithreaded environment.</p>\n<p>For Float and Double type variables, there is no atomic classes in this package. But you can use this technique described <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/5505460/java-is-there-no-atomicfloat-or-atomicdouble\">here</a>.</p>\n"
  } ],
